By Wang Weikai, special correspondent, southern weekend

Southern weekend intern, Gong Roushan

Responsible Editor | Gu CE, Zhang Yue

"This matter can not wait any longer, " Wang Zhonglin, the newly appointed member of the Standing Committee of the Hubei Provincial Party Committee and Secretary of the Wuhan Municipal Party Committee, said in a video conference on Feb. 16,2020.

He said the "thing" refers to a 3-day centralized screening, to strive to 3 days, home patients carpet, screening, thoroughly find out the "base number" of infected patients.

The day, February 5, Hubei Province, "should be collected, should be treated to rule" order issued 11 days have passed. That day, Hubei Province new pneumonia epidemic prevention and Control Command issued an order to suspected and confirmed cases of "should be collected, should be treated, " to ensure that all.

The word "collect" actually appeared more than twenty days ago, and has been mentioned again and again since then.

On January 24, the Wuhan government stressed the need to fully enter a "wartime" state, to ensure that fever patients receive timely treatment, to ensure that all suspected patients can receive unconditional treatment.

It was New Year's Eve, the second day of the city's closure, and many people were waiting in hospitals for a bed and a nucleic acid test.

Two days later, Wuhan again stressed the need for a "first-level response" to combat the situation, to achieve "a full diagnosis, a full stop, a full collection, a full stop, " and resolutely curb the spread of the epidemic.

Since then, General Secretary of the Communist Party of China Xi Jinping, Premier Li Keqiang and vice premier Sun Chunlan have stressed that all patients should be "collected. ".

Unfortunately, 22 days later, the "bottom number" of infected patients in Wuhan is still not clear, this long battle continues. Why is it so difficult for Wuhan to achieve the goal of "collecting all the revenues" ?

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On Feb. 12, a Chengguan vehicle helped transfer patients to a hospital. (Wang Weikai, southern weekend reporter / Photo)

1
The formation of Landslide dam

1

###The formation of Landslide dam

On February 13, Hubei Province and Wuhan Province both switched sides.

On that day, a record 13,436 new cases were diagnosed in Wuhan, six to seven times the number in previous days. It is worth noting that of these newly diagnosed cases, 92% were confirmed by clinical diagnosis, reaching 12,364 cases.

According to the official website of the Hubei Provincial Health and Health Commission, Hubei Province will include the number of clinically diagnosed cases into the number of confirmed cases from February 12, in line with the classification of cases published by other provinces in the country.

Previously, the nucleic acid reagent test was the only diagnostic standard for patients in Wuhan. In the early days of the outbreak, the supply of nucleic acid reagents was so inadequate that many suspected patients had to queue up to be tested.

On January 29, Yuan Hua, a Wuhan resident, reported to her Wufengli community in Hanyang District after a CT scan showed "a patchy ground glass shadow in her lung, " a highly suspected symptom of the patient. During this period, her husband's CT report also showed "lung infection. ".

But it was not until February 9 that they were notified of the community nucleic acid test. On February 12th and 13th, the couple received nucleic acid test results that were positive, but fortunately, both had mild cases.

According to official information on February 12,40 institutions in Wuhan have been able to carry out new coronavirus nucleic acid testing, with a daily detection capacity of 8,000 to 10,000 people.

The head of the Brand Department of Guangzhou Jinyu Medical Inspection Group, one of the official designated inspection agencies, told southern weekend that the company's testing capacity was only about 1,000 servings per day around January 31. Since then, the company has increased the number of people and machines, can now reach 3,000 people per day.

But there are also some patients on the Internet for help, their lungs have been white, clinical symptoms are very obvious, but because the nucleic acid test was negative, can not be identified as a confirmed patient, can not enter the designated hospital, leading to missed treatment time.

In early February, Li's mother began to develop symptoms of fever, fatigue and vomiting, but because her nucleic acid test was negative, she could not be identified as a confirmed patient and had to be quarantined at a nearby quarantine site.

It was not until 4pm on February 12th that the "good news" arrived -- Mother was finally "diagnosed" and transferred from quarantine to Vulcan Mountain Hospital. But to the Fire Mountain Hospital are critically ill patients, Li Wen's mother's lungs have also been completely white.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
It snowed heavily on Feb. 15 in Wuhan, and the Huoshenshan Hospital, which has treated 1,000 patients, was covered with snow. (Wang Weikai, southern weekend reporter / Photo)

Front-line doctors began to Whoo, should be CT imaging and other clinical diagnosis as the diagnostic criteria.

On Feb. 5, the COVID-19 released the fifth edition of its Diagnostic Program for pneumonia in infectious diseases, which includes CT findings in patients'clinical criteria. However, the new diagnostic criteria do not apply to Hubei Province. It was not until February 12 that this standard was applied in Hubei Province.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Mount Thor Hospital, under construction, Feb. 8. (Wang Weikai, southern weekend reporter / Photo)

2
Medical resources in short supply

2

###Medical resources in short supply

In the early stage of the outbreak, "one bed is hard to find" is another factor restricting the campaign of "collecting everything" .

At that time, the network of information for help, in addition to the help of nucleic acid testing, is the help of hospital beds. The news of overcrowded hospitals, long lines for treatment and doctors working 24 hours a day is still fresh in many people's minds today.

In addition to beds, there was a severe shortage of staff and resources.

On February 17, Jiao Yahui, deputy director of the medical and Health Administration Bureau of the National Health and Health Commission, made this point in an interview with CCTV's News 1 + 1 to answer a question on why the number of seriously ill patients in Wuhan remains high.

For a hospital, she said, 10 percent of the wards would normally be intensive care units, and in that amount of time, all the wards in the hospital would become intensive care units, there is not enough breathing apparatus, monitors and other equipment for resuscitation, and not enough doctors and nurses in the intensive care unit.

At the beginning of the epidemic, these only medical resources were not fully coordinated by government departments.

"No resources can be mobilized" and "no overall deployment" are Chen Peng's impressions of the initial "fight against the epidemic" . He was a ranking officer in Wuhan, and in this battle, he went to the front line of "fighting the epidemic" .

He recalled to southern weekend reporters that at that time the orders from the epidemic control headquarters were to strictly control the epidemic, but what troubled these grassroots workers was that, in addition to not knowing the patient's condition, as a district-level government, they have so few medical resources to mobilise that only hospitals like Wuhan's Red Cross Hospital can do so.

In this "epidemic" , the lack of not only hospital beds, but also isolation points. "should be collected" , to "four categories of people" for screening, admission, isolation, are confirmed patients, suspected patients, fever patients and close contacts. And according to the rules, different people are treated in different places.

In the early days of the outbreak, Wuhan Required "Home Quarantine" for suspected patients and those with mild illnesses because of the lack of beds and isolation points, a strategy that was a measure of desperation but also a failure, despite the possibility of infection from outside, but many of the families were infected during that time.

However, with the arrival of 20,000 provincial teams and the opening of Ryōkami-san hospitals and 11 shelter hospitals, the strain on medical resources has been greatly eased.

As of 2400 hours on February 17, there were 37,152 confirmed cases (including 9,222 severe cases) and 1,799 suspected cases in Wuhan, according to the NHS website. That means at least 38,951 beds are needed to ensure that all confirmed and suspected patients are admitted, a number that will continue to rise until the inflection point.

On Feb. 17, there were 45 designated hospitals in Wuhan, with 19,161 beds open, 18,086 beds used and 1,452 left, according to the Wuhan Municipal Health Commission's website. In addition, 12"Shelter Hospital" plan bed 20,461, has opened the bed 7566, has used the bed 6971.

Starting from February 7,8,800 beds for patients with mild illness will be released after students'dormitories are rebuilt in universities in Wuhan. Party schools of the Hubei Provincial Party Committee, some party schools and some hotels in the urban area of Wuhan have also been requisitioned to renovate the quarantine area.

3
Tough neighborhood canvass

3

###Tough neighborhood canvass

In order to achieve "due diligence" , community screening is one of the most important links.

Don't panic, the community grid will help you. This is a slogan often seen on the streets of Wuhan, where communities are managed in a grid format to keep track of the epidemic.

For this mega-city of more than 10 million people with a total area of 8,569.15 square kilometers, "Grid" management is an extremely complex and heavy work.

In the Office of a Community Council, southern weekend saw a grid worker's desk filled with forms, statistics, and information about the movement and health of everyone in his community. The grid worker told southern weekend that he calls residents hundreds of times a day to keep track of what's going on in the community.

But it's not enough to just call. They need to visit, ask about their temperature, and help take care of elderly people who are lonely or indisposed.

A street worker told southern weekend that when the neighborhood is searched, if residents are found to have fever, cough and other symptoms, they will be counted, filed, and the residents will be sent to the hospital for examination. The results of the hospital tests will be reported to the district, which will then report back to the street.

But this seemingly simple task is complicated. For example, in the district feedback form, the patient information does not specifically distinguish which street, they need to crawl in the form one by one to find, and ultimately pick out their own community.

In addition, some patients information only name and telephone, do not know where the specific residence, each street needs to call one by one to determine whether they belong to their own streets. There are also patients who are registered as residents, but live on another street, and the two streets need to communicate to determine who is responsible.

"We make a lot of phone calls every day, just like the community, " the street worker told southern weekend.

After finding the patient on their own street, the street will report the patient and the bed to the community, and the community will assist the confirmed and suspected patient to the hospital and the isolation point for treatment and isolation.

"When residents are unable to find beds, hospitals and streets send them to the community, and when the community tells them to, they go to the community and ask the community to help them with the beds. But we don't have the right to allocate beds, we can only wait for the arrangements in the districts and the streets,"a community secretary told southern weekend, "We were scared to get in touch with them. We were also scared of infection. "

There seems to be a vicious circle of community workers who need to come in, but are themselves close contacts, and some residents are reluctant to let them in.

"Don't say to go to the door to take a temperature, sometimes we can't even get into the building, " said the community secretary to southern weekend reporters.

Residential Areas in Wuhan require each household to leave the house only once every three days. The secretary's community also helps residents buy vegetables and other daily necessities. After buying back, some residents are afraid to come into contact with the staff, so they hang down a basket from the window and ask the staff to put vegetables and so on into the basket; Some are put on the first floor door, let the owner himself to take.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
"Grid workers" in Jiang'an District's Ming New community are checking residents' health information. (Wang Weikai, southern weekend reporter / Photo)

4
We're shorthanded

4

###We're shorthanded

Lack of personnel is the common feeling of community workers in Wuhan.

Take a community in Wuhan Qiao Estuary, which has more than 6,000 people and 11 community workers. This means that one worker has to deal with about 600 residents. Such a staffing ratio is a common phenomenon in Wuhan, a mega-city. In some communities, a "grid worker" is responsible for more than 1,000 residents.

The community was later investigated by Wuhan's disciplinary and supervisory authorities after a suspected patient hanged himself, and the community leader was given a warning by the party.

The community leader was deeply saddened by the tragedy in her district, but also felt powerless during an interview with southern weekend reporters. In the early days of the outbreak, the community suffered Major "attrition" of staff, half of whom were unable to work because of physical discomfort, and one who resigned out of fear of being infected. Only five or six people were able to "fight. ".

Communities are similar to village committees and are not part of the government. In addition, through a number of community interviews, southern weekend reporters learned that their salaries are not high, the secretary, director's salary after tax in more than 3,000 yuan, the general staff only more than 2,000 yuan.

At the same time, the urban areas as a whole district units and streets (towns) a total of more than 17,000 party members and cadres, all covering contact Baobao community (village) . This means that a total of 34,000 cadres and workers from all over the city have gone down to work in the community.

In one mid-sized Street in Jiang'an District, for example, about 50 cadres and workers sank into the street. The street has five neighborhoods, each with about 10 people.

However, according to a number of street and community workers, these sinking cadres and workers are mainly to assist the community to do a good job in the management of community entrances and exits, such as taking body temperature, registration information, and so on, rather than following the direct contact of community workers with residents, to get involved in more specific investigations.

In addition to the shortage of manpower, screening methods also affect the results of screening.

The above-mentioned community secretary to the southern weekend reporter, the current home and telephone investigation, mainly to inquire about temperature. But there are some "asymptomatic" patients in Wuhan. He worries that simply asking about body temperature will not give an accurate picture of residents'health.

"In the early days, the situation was even worse. There were fewer hospital beds and more people. Some residents deliberately hid their temperature and did not want to go to the hospital for an examination. Now there are fewer people in the hospital and many fewer residents to hide, " the secretary told southern weekend.

On February 10, Wuhan once published a "base number" , but was quickly questioned by netizens.

That night, at a press conference on the epidemic prevention and control work in Hubei Province, Ma Guoqiang, the then secretary of the Wuhan Municipal Party Committee, said that as of February 9, the percentage of households in Wuhan had reached 98.6 percent, and the percentage of people who had been investigated had reached 99 percent, and aim to have all suspected patients cleared by February 11.

After the news came out, some Wuhan local netizen began to tease, oneself belong to that did not be checked 1% . After February 11, there were still a number of suspected cases in Wuhan.

Even those who have been diagnosed have not been given beds immediately.

On February 14, Grandma Shen, 82, of the Qiao Estuary, was finally informed by the Jixianli Community Health Service Center that she could be admitted to the Wuhan Red Cross Hospital. It had been five days since her diagnosis.

But because of a brain stem hemorrhage, Shen was unable to walk normally, so she missed a bus sent by the headquarters to the community. She had to ask her son to drive her to the Wuhan Red Cross Hospital, where she was waiting for a specific bed.

February 17, Wuhan, "centralized network-style investigation" began, "do not leave a door, do not leave a person" is the requirements of the investigation.

On that day, southern weekend reporters repeatedly called the community, street workers who had been interviewed before the phone, all failed to get through. But early in the morning, according to local media in Wuhan, they began going door to door, asking questions from house to house.

Residents who don't want to cooperate, take their temperature, or go out for a while, register and then go back to work after a while.

The results of this investigation have been widely expected.

(at the interviewee's request, Chen Peng, Yuan Hua and Li Wen were given pseudonyms. Southern weekend reporter Ma Suping contributed to this report.)
